│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe loop-vectorizer crashes on an assertion in      │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF, which checks that the VPlan-based    │
│ cost model selects the same VF as the legacy cost model unless the selected   │
│ VPlan contains additional simplifications. In the reproducer, the VPlan-based │
│ model selects a scalar VF=1, while the legacy model selects a scalable        │
│ VF=<vscale x 4>, causing the assertion to fire.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's         │
│ Log:\nThe debug-only output shows no extra detail, but the GDB locals         │
│ indicate:\n- BestFactor.Width is scalar (1), implying the VPlan model did not │
│ find any profitable vector VFs.\n- LegacyVF.Width is scalable 4, meaning the  │
│ legacy model found vectorization profitable.\n- The BestPlan VFs set contains │
│ only scalar VF=1 for the selected plan.\nThis discrepancy points to           │
│ willGenerateVectors returning false for all vector VFs, causing the           │
│ VPlan-based model to skip vector candidates, while the legacy model proceeded │
│ and selected a vector VF.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe decision to         │
│ consider a VF candidate depends on willGenerateVectors(Plan, VF, TTI), which  │
│ is meant to conservatively check if the plan will actually produce values     │
│ assigned to vector registers. The current implementation uses a Visited set   │
│ of scalar types to avoid repeated checks across recipes. However, this        │
│ deduplication can cause false negatives: if a type is encountered in a        │
│ context where WillWiden returns false (e.g., a mask type or an ephemeral      │
│ recipe), later checks for the same scalar type used in a genuinely            │
│ vector-producing recipe (e.g., a predicated store of i8) are skipped due to   │
│ Visited short-circuiting. In our case, this results in no recipe being        │
│ recognized as vector-producing, leading willGenerateVectors to return false   │
│ for all VFs, even though the legacy model sees vectorization as profitable    │
│ and legal for VF=<vscale x 4> on RISC-V V.\nThis mismatch leads computeBestVF │
│ to keep BestFactor at scalar, while LegacyVF is scalable, and since           │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications is not true, the assertion              │
│ triggers.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- Edit Point 1 (remove the Visited   │
│ set declaration): Lines 4476-4478 in                                          │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp.\n  Rationale: Prevent        │
│ premature deduplication across recipes based solely on scalar type, which can │
│ hide genuine vector-generating operations later in the plan. This makes       │
│ willGenerateVectors conservative in favor of vector generation.\n  Change:    │
│ Delete the declaration and initialization of `DenseSet<Type *>                │
│ Visited;`.\n\n- Edit Point 2 (remove the Visited short-circuit): Lines        │
│ 4556-4559 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp.\n  Rationale:   │
│ Ensure every candidate recipe's type is evaluated by WillWiden, rather than   │
│ skipping due to a previous encounter of the same scalar type.\n  Change:      │
│ Delete the lines:\n    `if (!Visited.insert({ScalarTy}).second)\n             │
│ continue;`\n\nThese edits make willGenerateVectors check all relevant recipes │
│ and types, avoiding false negatives caused by the type-level deduplication    │
│ heuristic. As a result, if any recipe in the VPlan would use a vector         │
│ register (e.g., vector stores of i8 under predication or widened data paths), │
│ willGenerateVectors will correctly return true, allowing the VPlan cost model │
│ to consider vector VFs. This aligns the VPlan-based selection with the legacy │
│ model and prevents the assertion from firing.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy removing  │
│ the type-based deduplication in willGenerateVectors, we avoid missing genuine │
│ vector-generating operations and ensure the VPlan-based cost model considers  │
│ vector VFs when appropriate. This should resolve the disagreement with the    │
│ legacy cost model for the given reproducer, eliminating the assertion failure │
│ and allowing the pass to proceed. The change is conservative in the sense     │
│ that it only broadens the detection of vector generation, not the legality    │
