│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The loop-vectorizer crashes on an assertion in                                │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF, which checks that the VPlan-based    │
│ cost model selects the same VF as the legacy cost model unless the selected   │
│ VPlan contains additional simplifications. In the reproducer, the VPlan-based │
│ model selects a scalar VF=1, while the legacy model selects a scalable        │
│ VF=<vscale x 4>, causing the assertion to fire.                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug-only output shows no extra detail, but the GDB locals indicate:     │
│ - BestFactor.Width is scalar (1), implying the VPlan model did not find any   │
│ profitable vector VFs.                                                        │
│ - LegacyVF.Width is scalable 4, meaning the legacy model found vectorization  │
│ profitable.                                                                   │
│ - The BestPlan VFs set contains only scalar VF=1 for the selected plan.       │
│ This discrepancy points to willGenerateVectors returning false for all vector │
│ VFs, causing the VPlan-based model to skip vector candidates, while the       │
│ legacy model proceeded and selected a vector VF.                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The decision to consider a VF candidate depends on willGenerateVectors(Plan,  │
│ VF, TTI), which is meant to conservatively check if the plan will actually    │
│ produce values assigned to vector registers. The current implementation uses  │
│ a Visited set of scalar types to avoid repeated checks across recipes.        │
│ However, this deduplication can cause false negatives: if a type is           │
│ encountered in a context where WillWiden returns false (e.g., a mask type or  │
│ an ephemeral recipe), later checks for the same scalar type used in a         │
│ genuinely vector-producing recipe (e.g., a predicated store of i8) are        │
│ skipped due to Visited short-circuiting. In our case, this results in no      │
│ recipe being recognized as vector-producing, leading willGenerateVectors to   │
│ return false for all VFs, even though the legacy model sees vectorization as  │
│ profitable and legal for VF=<vscale x 4> on RISC-V V.                         │
│ This mismatch leads computeBestVF to keep BestFactor at scalar, while         │
│ LegacyVF is scalable, and since planContainsAdditionalSimplifications is not  │
│ true, the assertion triggers.                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - Edit Point 1 (remove the Visited set declaration): Lines 4476-4478 in       │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp.                              │
│   Rationale: Prevent premature deduplication across recipes based solely on   │
│ scalar type, which can hide genuine vector-generating operations later in the │
│ plan. This makes willGenerateVectors conservative in favor of vector          │
│ generation.                                                                   │
│   Change: Delete the declaration and initialization of `DenseSet<Type *>      │
│ Visited;`.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ - Edit Point 2 (remove the Visited short-circuit): Lines 4556-4559 in         │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp.                              │
│   Rationale: Ensure every candidate recipe's type is evaluated by WillWiden,  │
│ rather than skipping due to a previous encounter of the same scalar type.     │
│   Change: Delete the lines:                                                   │
│     `if (!Visited.insert({ScalarTy}).second)                                  │
│        continue;`                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ These edits make willGenerateVectors check all relevant recipes and types,    │
│ avoiding false negatives caused by the type-level deduplication heuristic. As │
│ a result, if any recipe in the VPlan would use a vector register (e.g.,       │
│ vector stores of i8 under predication or widened data paths),                 │
│ willGenerateVectors will correctly return true, allowing the VPlan cost model │
│ to consider vector VFs. This aligns the VPlan-based selection with the legacy │
│ model and prevents the assertion from firing.                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By removing the type-based deduplication in willGenerateVectors, we avoid     │
│ missing genuine vector-generating operations and ensure the VPlan-based cost  │
│ model considers vector VFs when appropriate. This should resolve the          │
│ disagreement with the legacy cost model for the given reproducer, eliminating │
│ the assertion failure and allowing the pass to proceed. The change is         │
│ conservative in the sense that it only broadens the detection of vector       │
│ generation, not the legality checks, and it keeps the function’s intent       │
│ intact.                                                                       │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
